04843nam a22007935i 9781400831326DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2009    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008313267 a10.1515/97814008313262doi  a(DE-B1597)453696  a(OCoLC)979726217  a(OCoLC)984545521  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aPHI0000002bisacsh1 aStroumsa, Sarah, eauthor.10aMaimonides in His World :bPortrait of a Mediterranean Thinker /cSarah Stroumsa.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJews, Christians, and Muslims from the Ancient to the Modern World ;v3400tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tChapter One. Maimonides and Mediterranean Culture -- tChapter Two. The Theological Context of Maimonides' Thought -- tChapter Three. An Almohad "Fundamentalist"? -- tChapter Four. La Longue Durée -- tChapter Five. A Critical Mind: Maimonides as Scientist -- tChapter Six. "From Moses to Moses": Maimonides' Vision of Perfection -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhile the great medieval philosopher, theologian, and physician Maimonides is acknowledged as a leading Jewish thinker, his intellectual contacts with his surrounding world are often described as related primarily to Islamic philosophy. Maimonides in His World challenges this view by revealing him to have wholeheartedly lived, breathed, and espoused the rich Mediterranean culture of his time. Sarah Stroumsa argues that Maimonides is most accurately viewed as a Mediterranean thinker who consistently interpreted his own Jewish tradition in contemporary multicultural terms. Maimonides spent his entire life in the Mediterranean region, and the religious and philosophical traditions that fed his thought were those of the wider world in which he lived. Stroumsa demonstrates that he was deeply influenced not only by Islamic philosophy but by Islamic culture as a whole, evidence of which she finds in his philosophy as well as his correspondence and legal and scientific writings. She begins with a concise biography of Maimonides, then carefully examines key aspects of his thought, including his approach to religion and the complex world of theology and religious ideas he encountered among Jews, Christians, Muslims, and even heretics; his views about science; the immense and unacknowledged impact of the Almohads on his thought; and his vision of human perfection. This insightful cultural biography restores Maimonides to his rightful place among medieval philosophers and affirms his central relevance to the study of medieval Islam.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aIntellectual lifexHistory. 0aPhilosophy, Medieval. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066258008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045953140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400831326423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400831326.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-045953-1  Princeton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-066258-0  PUP eBook-Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  